            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marcus Peterson\u2019s story is one of quiet purpose, shaped by family and a desire to untangle human complexities. He grew up in Sacramento, the only child of a high school history teacher and a hospital administrator. His childhood was stable and loving, but it was his mother\u2019s experience navigating a chronic illness that defined his path. He spent his teenage years watching her struggle with confusing appointment portals, opaque insurance jargon, and disconnected care providers. This frustration planted a seed: a profound interest in why systems built to help people so often failed them.\n\nThis led him to San Francisco State University to study Psychology, where he fell for the city's patchwork of cultures and ideas. While he initially considered clinical therapy, he realized his true passion was in fixing the flawed systems themselves. After graduating, he discovered the world of User Experience (UX) research, a perfect marriage of his psychological training and a desire for tangible impact. He found his niche in health tech, driven by the memory of his mother\u2019s struggles.\n\nNow at 38, Marcus is a Senior UX Researcher for a company developing platforms that integrate healthcare and educational support services. His $155,000 salary affords him a comfortable, if not extravagant, life in a rent-controlled one-bedroom apartment in the Mission District. He treasures his neighborhood's vibrant murals, diverse culinary scene, and lively energy. His daily 4.8-mile commute on the Muni J-Church line is a cherished ritual\u2014a time to read or listen to podcasts before diving into a day of interviews, data analysis, and advocating for user-centric design.\n\nHis social life is a close-knit circle of friends from college and former colleagues. A serious long-term relationship ended a few years ago, prompting a period of introspection and a renewed focus on his career and personal growth. Weekends often involve jogs through Golden Gate Park, browsing the Ferry Building Farmers Market, or taking short trips to hike in Marin. Marcus dreams of eventually leading a research team and, more personally, of finding a partner who shares his desire for meaningful connection. He feels deeply rooted in San Francisco, a city that provided him not just a career, but a purpose: to make life a little bit easier for the next person facing a difficult journey."
        },
