            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was sixteen, sitting at the kitchen table under the hum of the fluorescent light. His mom, a woman who ran hospital departments, was defeated by an insurance form. She let out a quiet, frustrated sigh, her finger lost in a paragraph of dense jargon. In that moment, a hot, protective anger bloomed in Marcus\u2019s chest. It wasn\u2019t just about the illness; it was about the systems designed to confuse and exhaust. He knew then he had to somehow fight that confusion for others, even if he didn't yet know how.\n\n2.\nCutting through Clarion Alley for the first time was a sensory overload that felt like coming home. He was nineteen, a new SF State student from Sacramento\u2019s quiet suburbs. The explosive color of the murals, the smell of street food, the mix of Spanish and English in the air\u2014it was all beautifully chaotic. Standing there, he felt a profound sense of arrival, a feeling that this city was big enough to hold all the messy, complicated parts of the world, and by extension, the messy, complicated parts of him.\n\n3.\nIt was a guest lecture in his final year of college that changed everything. A woman, a UX researcher, described mapping a cancer patient's \"journey\" through a hospital app\u2014not their medical path, but their emotional one. She talked about designing for fear and confusion. A light went on in Marcus's mind, so bright it was almost audible. This was it. This was the practical application of empathy he\u2019d been searching for, the perfect fusion of psychology and fixing what was broken. It was the answer to that long-ago night in the kitchen.\n\n4.\nIt was about six months after the breakup, on a foggy Saturday run through Golden Gate Park. Reaching the Dutch Windmill, he stopped, the damp air cold in his lungs as he stared at the grey churn of the Pacific. There was no one to text, no dinner plans to confirm. In the silence, what he felt wasn't loneliness, but a quiet, bracing solitude. He realized he had to be his own foundation first. The run back through the park, as the fog began to lift, felt lighter, more determined.\n\n5.\nLast year, during a user interview, an elderly man's voice cracked. \"I feel so stupid,\" he said, talking about a platform Marcus\u2019s company had built. \"I just want to see my son\u2019s school records.\" Marcus saw his own mother in the man\u2019s frustrated eyes. He didn\u2019t just listen; he absorbed the man's pain. Later, he championed a redesign based on that conversation, using the man's exact words in his presentation. When the simpler interface launched, it felt more meaningful than any promotion. It felt like a promise kept."
